2. Dot Product (Inner Product)
Measures the product of the magnitudes of two vectors and the cosine of the angle between them.
3. Cosine Similarity
Measures the cosine of the angle between two vectors, ignoring their differences in magnitude.

The Nearest Neighbor ProblemGiven a query vector $q$ and a database of $n$ vectors, how do we find the $k$ closest vectors?
  Exact k-NN (k-Nearest Neighbors)Calculates the similarity metric between the query vector $q$ and every single vector in the database.
  Pros: $100\%$ perfect accuracy (recall).Cons: Time complexity is O(d . n) where n is the number of vectors and d is dimensions. 
  At scale, this exhaustive search is way too slow for real-time applications.
  ANN (Approximate Nearest Neighbor)To achieve sub-second latencies, vector databases trade a tiny bit of accuracy for massive speedups using ANN algorithms.
  Instead of searching everything, they use pre-calculated index structures to jump directly to the neighborhood of the target vector and search only a fraction of the dataset.

